  "articleSummary": "This technical analysis explores \"Guerrilla\" strategies for designing consistent, predictable TypeScript interfaces, specifically for semi-structured API data. The author argues for a middle ground between monolithic objects and fragmented named types, proposing three specific techniques: deriving sub-types from primary structures using indexed access types, utilizing mix-ins for logical field composition, and organizing types via namespaces. The tone is practical and experimental, aimed at intermediate TypeScript developers seeking to improve code reusability and IDE ergonomics (DX) without sacrificing readability. The article frames these methods as \"guerrilla\" tactics—non-traditional but effective ways to maintain \"durable\" models and avoid naming variances in complex systems.",
